    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies yacht engineers on the income they actually earn at sea &mdash; <strong>not on the W-2 line a U.S. underwriter is trained to read</strong>. A Chief Engineer on a 60-meter motor yacht with a $180K Cayman-flagged W-2 plus rotation longevity, a Second Engineer on a sailing yacht with a Y2-equivalent SV Chief Engineer certificate building toward Y1, an ETO maintaining the navigation electronics on a 50-meter, and a yacht engineer transitioning to a shore-based marine-systems consultancy each get qualified using the method that fits their pay structure. We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other yacht professions, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/yacht-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">yacht professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
